{
  "What are the three types of regions identified in geography?": "",
  "Urban, suburban, and rural": "",
  "Continental, national, and local": "",
  "Political, economic, and cultural": "",
  "Formal, functional, and perceptual (vernacular)": "",
  "Geographers identify three types of regions: formal (defined by uniform characteristics), functional (organized around a central node or activity), and perceptual/vernacular (defined by people's subjective perceptions and feelings).": "",
  "What defines a formal region?": "",
  "An area defined by one or more uniform characteristics shared throughout, such as language, climate, or government": "",
  "An area organized around a central point": "",
  "An area with formal government institutions": "",
  "An area defined by people's perceptions": "",
  "A formal (uniform) region is defined by a shared characteristic that is consistent throughout the area. Examples include countries (political boundaries), climate zones, and language regions like French-speaking Quebec.": "",
  "What defines a functional region?": "",
  "An area that functions as a national park": "",
  "An area organized around a focal point or node, connected by flows of activity": "",
  "An area imagined by residents": "",
  "An area with the same physical characteristics": "",
  "A functional (nodal) region is organized around a central hub or node and defined by the connections and interactions radiating from it. A city's commuter zone, newspaper circulation area, or pizza delivery zone are functional regions.": "",
  "What is a perceptual (vernacular) region?": "",
  "A region defined by economic output": "",
  "A region that exists in people's minds based on shared cultural identity, feelings, or attitudes": "",
  "A region that can only be perceived through technology": "",
  "A region defined by precise geographic coordinates": "",
  "A perceptual (vernacular) region is defined by people's mental maps and cultural perceptions rather than precise boundaries. 'The South,' 'the Midwest,' and 'the Middle East' are perceptual regions whose exact boundaries differ between individuals.": "",
